04629nam a22005295i 9780300147742DE-B159720200424112023.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200424t19981998ctu    fo  d z      eng d  a97803001477427 a10.12987/97803001477422doi  a(DE-B1597)486758  a(OCoLC)1024045097  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  actucUS-CT 4aJC421b.W43 1998eb 7aPOL0110002bisacsh04a327.1/722200aNever at War /cWilliam I. Hitchcock, Paul Kennedy. 1aNew Haven, CT : bYale University Press, c[1998] 4cÂ©1998  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tCHAPTER ONE. Investigating the Puzzle of Democratic Peace -- tCHAPTER TWO. Ancient Greece: Definitions and a Pattern of Peace -- tCHAPTER THREE. Medieval Italy: Wars Without States -- tCHAPTER FOUR. The Rise of Republican States, Ideals, and Alliances -- tCHAPTER FIVE. The Political Culture of Peace -- tCHAPTER SIX. The Swiss Republics: Defining an Enemy -- tCHAPTER SEVEN. Oligarchy, Intervention, and Civil War -- tCHAPTER EIGHT. Republics Versus Autocracies -- tCHAPTER NINE. Well-Established Republics Versus Authoritarian Regimes -- tCHAPTER TEN. Well-Established Republics Versus Newborn Republics -- tCHAPTER ELEVEN. Authoritarian Diplomacy -- tCHAPTER TWELVE. Republican Diplomacy -- tCHAPTER THIRTEEN. Imperialist Aggression by Democracies -- tCHAPTER FOURTEEN. Leagues of Republics -- tCHAPTER FIFTEEN. Crusading for Democracy -- tAPPENDIX. Military Confrontations Between Approximately Republican Regimes of the Same Kind -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis lively survey of the history of conflict between democracies reveals a remarkable-and tremendously important-finding: fully democratic nations have never made war on other democracies. Furthermore, historian Spencer R. Weart concludes in this thought-provoking book, they probably never will. Building his argument on some forty case studies ranging through history from ancient Athens to Renaissance Italy to modern America, the author analyzes for the first time every instance in which democracies or regimes like democracies have confronted each other with military force. Weart establishes a consistent set of definitions of democracy and other key terms, then draws on an array of international sources to demonstrate the absence of war among states of a particular democratic type. His survey also reveals the new and unexpected finding of a still broader zone of peace among oligarchic republics, even though there are more of such minority-controlled governments than democracies in history. In addition, Weart discovers that peaceful leagues and confederations-the converse of war-endure only when member states are democracies or oligarchies. With the help of related findings in political science, anthropology, and social psychology, the author explores how the political culture of democratic leaders prevents them from warring against others who are recognized as fellow democrats and how certain beliefs and behaviors lead to peace or war. Weart identifies danger points for democracies, and he offers crucial, practical information to help safeguard peace in the future.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aDemocracyxHistory. 0aPeacexHistory. 0aWarxHistory. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / General.2bisacsh1 aHitchcock, William I., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKennedy, Paul, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press eBook Package Archivez978311053801440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300147742423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9